# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: differential-pair
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] In electronics, the **common mode rejection ratio** (**CMRR**) of a differential amplifier (or other device) is a metric used to quantify the ability of the device to reject common-mode signals, i.e. those that appear simultaneously and in-phase on both inputs.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] An ideal differential amplifier would have infinite CMRR, however this is not achievable in practice.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] A high CMRR is required when a differential signal must be amplified in the presence of a possibly large common-mode input, such as strong electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] An example is audio transmission over balanced line in sound reinforcement or recording.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Ideally, a differential amplifier takes the voltages, $V_{+}$ and $V_{-}$ on its two inputs and produces an output voltage $V_{\mathrm {o} }=A_{\mathrm {d} }(V_{+}-V_{-})$ , where $A_{\mathrm {d} }$ is the differential gain.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] where $A_{\mathrm {cm} }$ is the "common-mode gain", which is typically much smaller than the differential gain.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] As differential gain should exceed common-mode gain, this will be a positive number, and the higher the better.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR is a very important specification, as it indicates how much of the unwanted common-mode signal will appear in the output, typically a measurement of some quantity.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The value of the CMRR often depends on signal frequency, and must be specified as a function thereof.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] It is often important in reducing noise on transmission lines.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] For example, when measuring the voltage of a thermocouple in a noisy environment, the electrical noise from the environment appears as an offset on both input leads, making it a common-mode voltage signal.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR of the measurement instrument determines the attenuation applied to the offset or noise.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] CMRR is an important feature of operational amplifiers, difference amplifiers and instrumentation amplifiers, and can be found in the datasheet.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR often varies with the frequency of the common-mode signal, and is often much higher at higher gain settings.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The key to achieving a high CMRR is usually the use of very precisely matched resistors (better than 0.1%) to minimise any difference in the amplification of the negative and positive sides of the signal.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Single-chip instrumentation amplifiers typically have laser-trimmed resistors to achieve a CMRR in excess of 100 dB, sometimes even 130 dB.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] Here, port1 is a single-ended input, and ports 2 and 3 are differential outputs.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] The CMRR of the balun represents the smallness of the gain and phase error between the differential outputs.
[src:differential-pair/common-mode-rejection-ratio] If the phase difference between the differential outputs of the balun is close to 180° and the amplitudes are equal, the CMRR will be high.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] A **differential amplifier** is a type of electronic amplifier that amplifies the difference between two input voltages but suppresses any voltage common to the two inputs.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Single amplifiers are usually implemented by either adding the appropriate feedback resistors to a standard op-amp, or with a dedicated integrated circuit containing internal feedback resistors.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] It is also a common sub-component of larger integrated circuits handling analog signals.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In practice, however, the gain is not quite equal for the two inputs.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This means, for instance, that if $V_{\text{in}}^{+}$ and $V_{\text{in}}^{-}$ are equal, the output will not be zero, as it would be in the ideal case.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] where $A_{\text{c}}$ is called the common-mode gain of the amplifier.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] As differential amplifiers are often used to null out noise or bias voltages that appear at both inputs, a low common-mode gain is usually desired.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The common-mode rejection ratio (CMRR), usually defined as the ratio between differential-mode gain and common-mode gain, indicates the ability of the amplifier to accurately cancel voltages that are common to both inputs.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In a perfectly symmetric differential amplifier, $A_{\text{c}}$ is zero, and the CMRR is infinite.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Note that a differential amplifier is a more general form of amplifier than one with a single input; by grounding one input of a differential amplifier, a single-ended amplifier results.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Modern differential amplifiers are usually implemented with a basic two-transistor circuit called a *“long-tailed” pair* or *differential pair*.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This circuit was originally implemented using a pair of vacuum tubes.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The circuit works the same way for all three-terminal devices with current gain.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The bias points of “long-tail” resistor circuit are largely determined by Ohm's law and less so by active-component characteristics.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was developed from earlier knowledge of push–pull circuit techniques and measurement bridges.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] An early circuit which closely resembles a long-tailed pair was published by British neurophysiologist Bryan Matthews in 1934, and it seems likely that this was intended to be a true long-tailed pair but was published with a drawing error.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The earliest definite long-tailed pair circuit appears in a patent submitted by Alan Blumlein in 1936.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] By the end of the 1930s the topology was well established and had been described by various authors, including Frank Offner (1937), Otto Schmitt (1937) and Jan Friedrich Toennies (1938), and it was particularly used for detection and measurement of physiological impulses.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The long-tailed pair was very successfully used in early British computing, most notably the Pilot ACE model and descendants, Maurice Wilkes’ EDSAC, and probably others designed by people who worked with Blumlein or his peers.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] One disadvantage is that the output voltage swing (typically ±10–20 V) was imposed upon a high DC voltage (200 V or so), requiring care in signal coupling, usually some form of wide-band DC coupling.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Many computers of this time tried to avoid this problem by using only AC-coupled pulse logic, which made them very large and overly complex (ENIAC: 18,000 tubes for a 20-digit calculator) or unreliable.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] DC-coupled circuitry became the norm after the first generation of vacuum-tube computers.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] A differential (long-tailed, emitter-coupled) pair amplifier consists of two amplifying stages with common (emitter, source or cathode) degeneration.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] With two inputs and two outputs, this forms a differential amplifier stage (Figure 2).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The two bases (or grids or gates) are inputs which are differentially amplified (subtracted and multiplied) by the transistor pair; they can be fed with a differential (balanced) input signal, or one input could be grounded to form a phase splitter circuit.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] An amplifier with differential output can drive a floating load or another stage with differential input.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] If the differential output is not desired, then only one output can be used (taken from just one of the collectors (or anodes or drains), disregarding the other output; this configuration is referred to as *single-ended output*.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The gain is half that of the stage with differential output.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] To avoid sacrificing gain, a differential to single-ended converter can be utilized.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This is often implemented as a current mirror (Figure 3, below).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The emitter-coupled amplifier is compensated for temperature drifts, VBE is cancelled, and the Miller effect and transistor saturation are avoided.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] That is why it is used to form emitter-coupled amplifiers (avoiding Miller effect), phase splitter circuits (obtaining two inverse voltages), ECL gates and switches (avoiding transistor saturation), etc.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] To explain the circuit operation, four particular modes are isolated below although, in practice, some of them act simultaneously and their effects are superimposed.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In contrast with classic amplifying stages that are biased from the side of the base (and so they are highly β-dependent), the differential pair is directly biased from the side of the emitters by sinking/injecting the total quiescent current.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The series negative feedback (the emitter degeneration) makes the transistors act as voltage stabilizers; it forces them to adjust their VBE voltages (base currents) to pass the quiescent current through their collector-emitter junctions.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] So, due to the negative feedback, the quiescent current depends only slightly on the transistor's β.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The biasing base currents needed to evoke the quiescent collector currents usually come from the ground, pass through the input sources and enter the bases.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] So, the sources have to be galvanic (DC) to ensure paths for the biasing current and low resistive enough to not create significant voltage drops across them.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Otherwise, additional DC elements should be connected between the bases and the ground (or the positive power supply).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In common mode (the two input voltages change in the same directions), the two voltage (emitter) followers cooperate with each other working together on the common high-resistive emitter load (the "long tail").
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] They all together increase or decrease the voltage of the common emitter point (figuratively speaking, they together "pull up" or "pull down" it so that it moves).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In addition, the dynamic load "helps" them by changing its instant ohmic resistance in the same direction as the input voltages (it increases when the voltage increases and vice versa.) thus keeping up constant total resistance between the two supply rails.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] There is a full (100%) negative feedback; the two input base voltages and the emitter voltage change simultaneously while the collector currents and the total current do not change.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] As a result, the output collector voltages do not change as well.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The collector resistors can be replaced by a current mirror (the top blue section in Fig.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] 3), whose output part acts as an active load.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Thus the differential collector current signal is converted to a single-ended voltage signal without the intrinsic 50% losses, so the gain is doubled.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This is achieved by copying the input collector current from the left to the right side, where the magnitudes of the two input signals add.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] For this purpose, the input of the current mirror is connected to the left output, and the output of the current mirror is connected to the right output of the differential amplifier.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The current mirror copies the left collector current and passes it through the right transistor that produces the right collector current.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] At this right output of the differential amplifier, the two signal currents (pos. and neg. current changes) are subtracted.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In this case (differential input signal), they are equal and opposite.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Thus, the difference is twice the individual signal currents (Δ*I* − (−Δ*I*) = 2Δ*I*), and the differential to single-ended conversion is completed without gain losses.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] 4 shows the transmission characteristic of this circuit.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The quiescent current has to be constant to ensure constant collector voltages at common mode.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This requirement is not so important in the case of a differential output, since although their two collector voltages will vary simultaneously their difference (the output voltage) will not vary.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] But in the case of a single-ended output, it is extremely important to keep a constant current since the output collector voltage will vary.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Thus the higher the resistance of the current source $R_{\text{e}}$ in the original circuit of Fig.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] 2, the lower (better) is the common-mode gain $A_{\text{c}}$ .
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The constant current needed could be produced by connecting an element (resistor) with very high resistance between the shared emitter node and the supply rail (negative for NPN and positive for PNP transistors), but that requires a high supply voltage.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] So in more sophisticated designs, an element with high differential (dynamic) resistance approximating a constant current source/sink (the bottom of Fig.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] It is usually implemented by a current mirror because of its high compliance voltage (small voltage drop across the output transistor).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] It is possible to connect a floating source between the two bases, but it is necessary to ensure paths for the biasing base currents.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In the case of galvanic source, only one resistor has to be connected between one of the bases and the ground.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The biasing current will enter directly this base and indirectly (through the input source) the other one.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] If the source is capacitive, two resistors have to be connected between the two bases and the ground to ensure different paths for the base currents.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The input impedance of the differential pair highly depends on the input mode.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] At common mode, the two parts behave as common-collector stages with high emitter loads; so, the input impedances are extremely high.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] At differential mode, they behave as common-emitter stages with grounded emitters; so, the input impedances are low.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The output impedance of the differential pair is high (especially for the improved differential pair with a current mirror as shown in Figure 3).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The common-mode input voltage can vary between the two supply rails but cannot closely reach them since some voltage drops (minimum 1 volt) have to remain across the output transistors of the two current mirrors.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] An operational amplifier, or op-amp, is a differential amplifier with very high differential-mode gain, very high input impedance, and low output impedance.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] An op-amp differential amplifier can be built with predictable and stable gain by applying *negative* feedback (Figure 5).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Some kinds of differential amplifier usually include several simpler differential amplifiers.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] For example, a fully differential amplifier, an instrumentation amplifier, or an isolation amplifier are often built from a combination of several op-amps.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Differential amplifiers are found in many circuits that utilize series negative feedback (op-amp follower, non-inverting amplifier, etc.), where one input is used for the input signal, the other for the feedback signal (usually implemented by operational amplifiers).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] For comparison, the old-fashioned inverting single-ended op-amps from the early 1940s could realize only parallel negative feedback by connecting additional resistor networks (an op-amp inverting amplifier is the most popular example).
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] A common application is for the control of motors or servos, as well as for signal amplification applications.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In discrete electronics, a common arrangement for implementing a differential amplifier is the long-tailed pair, which is also usually found as the differential element in most op-amp integrated circuits.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] A long-tailed pair can be used as an analog multiplier with the differential voltage as one input and the biasing current as another.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] A differential amplifier is used as the input stage emitter coupled logic gates and as switch.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] When used as a switch, the "left" base/grid is used as signal input and the "right" base/grid is grounded; output is taken from the right collector/plate.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] When the input is zero or negative, the output is close to zero (but can be not saturated); when the input is positive, the output is most-positive, dynamic operation being the same as the amplifier use described above.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The differential amplifier is used in the cathode follower oscillator.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] The advantages are high impedance of the differential amplifier input and output and small phase shift between input and output.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] This application uses only one input and one output of the differential amplifier.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In case the operational amplifier's (non-ideal) input bias current or differential input impedance are a significant effect, one can select a feedback network that improves the effect of common-mode input signal and bias.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] In Figure 6, current generators model the input bias current at each terminal; *I*+b and *I*−b represent the input bias current at terminals *V*+ and *V*− respectively.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] which implies that the closed-loop gain for the differential signal is *V*+in − *V*−in, but the common-mode gain is identically zero.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] It also implies that the common-mode input bias current has cancelled out, leaving only the input offset current *I*Δb = *I*+b − *I*−b still present, and with a coefficient of *R*i.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] It is as if the input offset current is equivalent to an input offset voltage acting across an input resistance *R*i, which is the source resistance of the feedback network into the input terminals.
[src:differential-pair/differential-amplifier] Finally, as long as the open-loop voltage gain *A*ol is much larger than unity, the closed-loop voltage gain is *R*f/*R*i, the value one would obtain through the rule-of-thumb analysis known as "virtual ground".
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In electronics, **emitter-coupled logic** (**ECL**) is a high-speed integrated circuit bipolar transistor logic family.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL uses a bipolar junction transistor (BJT) differential amplifier with single-ended input and limited emitter current to avoid the saturated (fully on) region of operation and the resulting slow turn-off behavior.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As the current is steered between two legs of an emitter-coupled pair, ECL is sometimes called *current-steering logic* (CSL), *current-mode logic* (CML) or *current-switch emitter-follower* (CSEF) logic.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In ECL, the transistors are never in saturation, the input and output voltages have a small swing (0.8 V), the input impedance is high and the output impedance is low.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As a result, the transistors change states quickly, gate delays are low, and the fanout capability is high.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In addition, the essentially constant current draw of the differential amplifiers minimizes delays and glitches due to supply-line inductance and capacitance, and the complementary outputs decrease the propagation time of the whole circuit by reducing inverter count.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL's major disadvantage is that each gate continuously draws current, which means that it requires (and dissipates) significantly more power than those of other logic families, especially when quiescent.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The equivalent of emitter-coupled logic made from FETs is called source-coupled logic (SCFL).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] A variation of ECL in which all signal paths and gate inputs are differential is known as differential current switch (DCS) logic.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL was invented in August 1956 at IBM by Hannon S.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Originally called *current-steering logic*, it was used in the Stretch, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 computers.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The logic was also called a current-mode circuit.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] It was also used to make the IBM Advanced Solid Logic Technology (ASLT) circuits in the IBM 360/91.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Yourke's current switch was a differential amplifier whose input logic levels were different from the output logic levels.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] "In current mode operation, however, the output signal consists of voltage levels which vary about a reference level different from the input reference level." In Yourke's design, the two logic reference levels differed by 3 volts.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Consequently, two complementary versions were used: an NPN version and a PNP version.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The NPN output could drive PNP inputs, and vice versa.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Instead of alternating NPN and PNP stages, another coupling method employed Zener diodes and resistors to shift the output logic levels to be the same as the input logic levels.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Beginning in the early 1960s, ECL circuits were implemented on monolithic integrated circuits.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] They consisted of a differential-amplifier input stage to perform logic followed by an emitter-follower stage to drive outputs and shift the output voltages so they will be compatible with the inputs.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The emitter-follower output stages could also be used to perform wired-or logic.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Motorola introduced their first digital monolithic integrated circuit line, MECL I, in 1962.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Motorola developed several improved series, with MECL II in 1966, MECL III in 1968 with 1-nanosecond gate propagation time and 300 MHz flip-flop toggle rates, and the 10,000 series (with lower power consumption and controlled edge speeds) in 1971.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The MECL 10H family was introduced in 1981.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Fairchild introduced the F100K family in 1975.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The ECLinPS ("ECL in picoseconds") family was introduced in 1987.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECLinPS has 500 ps single-gate delay and 1.1 GHz flip-flop toggle frequency.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The ECLinPS family parts are available from multiple sources, including Arizona Microtek, Micrel (subsequently acquired by Microchip Technology Inc.), National Semiconductor, and ON Semiconductor.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The high power consumption of ECL meant that it has been used mainly when high speed is a vital requirement.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Older high-end mainframe computers, such as the Enterprise System/9000 members of IBM's ESA/390 computer family, used ECL, as did the Cray-1, and first-generation Amdahl mainframes.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] (Current IBM mainframes use CMOS.) Beginning in 1975, Digital Equipment Corporation's highest performance processors were all based on multi-chip ECL CPUs—from the ECL KL10 through the ECL VAX 8000 and finally the VAX 9000.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] By 1991, the CMOS NVAX was launched, which offered comparable performance to the VAX 9000 despite costing 1/25 as much and consuming considerably less power.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Some of these computer designs used ECL gate arrays.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL is based on an emitter-coupled (long-tailed) pair, shaded red in the figure on the right.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The left half of the pair (shaded yellow) consists of two parallel-connected input transistors T1 and T2 (an exemplary two-input gate is considered) implementing NOR logic.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As a result, the common emitter resistor RE acts nearly as a current source.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The output voltages at the collector load resistors RC1 and RC3 are shifted and buffered to the inverting and non-inverting outputs by the emitter followers T4 and T5 (shaded blue).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The output emitter resistors RE4 and RE5 do not exist in all versions of ECL.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In some cases 50 Ω line termination resistors connected between the bases of the input transistors and −2 V of a driven gate act as emitter resistors of the driving gate.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The ECL circuit operation is considered below with assumption that the input voltage is applied to T1 base, while T2 input is unused or a logical "0" is applied.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] During the transition, the core of the circuit – the emitter-coupled pair (T1 and T3) – acts as a differential amplifier with single-ended input.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The long-tail current source (RE) sets the total current flowing through the two legs of the pair.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The input voltage controls the current flowing through the transistors by sharing it between the two legs, steering it all to one side when not near the switching point.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The gain is higher than at the end states (see below) and the circuit switches quickly.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] At low input voltage (logical "0") or at high input voltage (logical "1") the differential amplifier is overdriven.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The transistor (T1 or T3) is cutoff and the other (T3 or T1) is in active linear region acting as a common-emitter stage with emitter degeneration that takes all the current, starving the other cutoff transistor.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The active transistor is loaded with the relatively high emitter resistance *R*E that introduces a significant negative feedback (emitter degeneration).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] To prevent saturation of the active transistor so that the diffusion time that slows the recovery from saturation will not be involved in the logic delay, the emitter and collector resistances are chosen such that at maximum input voltage some voltage is left across the transistor.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The residual gain is low (*K* = *R*C/*R*E < 1).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The circuit is insensitive to the input voltage variations and the transistor stays firmly in active linear region.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The input resistance is high because of the series negative feedback.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The cutoff transistor breaks the connection between its input and output.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As a result, its input voltage does not affect the output voltage.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The input resistance is high again since the base-emitter junction is cutoff.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Other noteworthy characteristics of the ECL family include the fact that the large current requirement is approximately constant, and does not depend significantly on the state of the circuit.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] This means that ECL circuits generate relatively little power noise, unlike other logic types which draw more current when switching than quiescent.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In cryptographic applications, ECL circuits are also less susceptible to side channel attacks such as differential power analysis.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The propagation time for this arrangement can be less than a nanosecond, including the signal delay getting on and off the IC package.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Some type of ECL has always been the fastest logic family.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Radiation hardening: While normal commercial-grade chips can withstand 100 gray (10 krad), many ECL devices are operational after 100,000 gray (10 Mrad).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL circuits usually operate with negative power supplies (positive end of the supply is connected to ground).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] (Other logic families ground the negative end of the power supply.) This is done mainly to minimize the influence of the power supply variations on the logic levels.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL is more sensitive to noise on the VCC and is relatively immune to noise on VEE.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Because ground should be the most stable voltage in a system, ECL is specified with a positive ground.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In this connection, when the supply voltage varies, the voltage drops across the collector resistors change slightly (in the case of emitter constant current source, they do not change at all).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As the collector resistors are firmly "tied up" to ground, the output voltages "move" slightly (or not at all).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] If the negative end of the power supply was grounded, the collector resistors would be attached to the positive rail.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] As the constant voltage drops across the collector resistors change slightly (or not at all), the output voltages follow the supply voltage variations and the two circuit parts act as constant current level shifters.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In this case, the voltage divider R1-R2 compensates the voltage variations to some extent.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The positive power supply has another disadvantage — the output voltages will vary slightly (±0.4 V) against the background of high constant voltage (+3.9 V).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] Another reason for using a negative power supply is protection of the output transistors from an accidental short circuit developing between output and ground (but the outputs are not protected from a short circuit with the negative rail).
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The value of the supply voltage is chosen so that sufficient current flows through the compensating diodes D1 and D2 and the voltage drop across the common emitter resistor RE is adequate.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] ECL circuits available on the open market usually operated with logic levels incompatible with other families.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] This meant that interoperation between ECL and other logic families, such as the popular TTL family, required additional interface circuits.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The fact that the high and low logic levels are relatively close meant that ECL suffers from small noise margins, which can be troublesome.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] At least one manufacturer, IBM, made ECL circuits for use in the manufacturer's own products.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] The power supplies were substantially different from those used in the open market.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] A common misconception is that PECL devices are slightly different from ECL devices.
[src:differential-pair/emitter-coupled-logic] In fact, every ECL device is also a PECL device.
